block subSubContent
	h3
		b Exponents and logarithms.
	p Previously we defined addition and multiplication in terms of successive use of the sucessor function. That is, the definition of addition was:
	p $$\forall a \in \mathbb{N} (a+0=a)$$
	p $$\forall a b \in \mathbb{N} (a+s(b)=s(a+b))$$
	p And similarly for multiplication:
	p $$\forall a \in \mathbb{N} (a.0=0)$$
	p $$\forall a b \in \mathbb{N} (a.s(b)=a.b+a)$$
	p Additional functions could also be defined, following the same pattern:
	p $$\forall a \in \mathbb{N} (a\oplus _n 0=c)$$
	p $$\forall a b \in \mathbb{N} (a\oplus _{n} s(b)=(a\oplus_{n} b)\oplus_{n-1}a)$$

	h3
		b Powers
	p Exponents can also be defined:
	h3
		b Axioms
	p $$\forall a \in \mathbb{N} a^0=1$$
	p $$\forall a b \in \mathbb{N} a^{s(b)}=a^b.a$$
	h3
		b Example
	p So \(2^2\) can be calculated like:
	p $$2^2=2^{s(1)}$$
	p $$2^{s(1)}=2.2^1$$
	p $$2.2^1=2.2.2^0$$
	p $$2.2.2^0=2.2.1$$
	p $$2.2.1=4$$

	p Unlike addition and multiplication, exponention is not commutative. That is
	p $$a^b\ne b^a$$


	h3
		b Exponential rules
	p $$a^ba^c=a^{b+c}$$
	p $$(a^b)^c=a^{bc}$$
	p $$(ab)^c=a^cb^c$$
